edia spaces and seek to forge more equal relations both within Mexico and beyond its borders. It is within these spaces that Ayuujk people carve out their own, at times conflicting, visions of development, modernity, gender, and what it means to be indigenous in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aMixe mass mediazMexico. 0aMixe mass mediazUnited States. 7aPhotography / Techniques / Cinematography & Videography.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  aaudience.  aaudiovisual.  aayuujik people.  acamera.  acinematography.  adocumentary.  aengaging.  aequal relations.  aethnic studies.  aethnopolitical movements.  ahispanic american demographic studies.  ahispanic american studies.  aindigenous people.  ainternet access.  alife changes.  amedia forms.  amedia genres.  amedia.  amexican indigenous people.  apage turner.  aphotography equipment.  aphotography.  apolitics.  aradio.  arealistic.  atamazulapam mixe.  atechnology.  atelevision.  atransnational migration.  avideo.  avideography.  aworking class.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311099821440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781785335839?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781785335839423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781785335839/original  a978-3-11-099821-4  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK